Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section details the required encoding and special character conventions for shader files.
Key Rule: Shader files must use line feed (LF) characters for line breaks.
Key Rule: Shader files must end with a single line feed character.
Key Rule: Shader files must use UTF-8 encoding without a byte order mark.
Key Rule: Shader files must use Tabs for indentation.
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section of the Shaders Style Guide covers indentation rules for GLSL code within Godot.

Indentation
Each indent level should be one tab greater than the block containing it.

GDScript:
void fragment() {
    COLOR = vec3(1.0, 1.0, 1.0);
}

GDScript:
void fragment() {
        COLOR = vec3(1.0, 1.0, 1.0);
}

Use 2 indent levels to distinguish continuation lines from regular code blocks.

GDScript:
vec2 st = vec2(
        atan(NORMAL.x, NORMAL.z),
        acos(NORMAL.y));

GDScript:
vec2 st = vec2(
    atan(NORMAL.x, NORMAL.z),
    acos(NORMAL.y));
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section details the recommended style for line breaks and blank lines in Godot shaders, emphasizing the use of 1TBS style and always including braces for statements.
For a general indentation rule, follow the "1TBS Style" which recommends placing the brace associated with a control statement on the same line. Always use braces for statements, even if they only span one line. This makes them easier to refactor and avoids mistakes when adding more lines to an if statement or similar.

GDScript:
```glsl
void fragment() {
    if (true) {
        // ...
    }
}
```

GDScript:
```glsl
void fragment()
{
    if (true)
        // ...
}
```
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section details style guidelines for writing GLSL shaders in Godot, focusing on function spacing and internal code structure.

GDScript:
Surround function definitions with one (and only one) blank line.

    void do_something() {
        // ...
    }

    void fragment() {
        // ...
    }

Use one (and only one) blank line inside functions to separate logical sections.
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section provides guidelines for line length in shader code.
Line length
Keep individual lines of code under 100 characters.
If you can, try to keep lines under 80 characters. This helps to read the code on small displays and with two shaders opened side-by-side in an external text editor. For example, when looking at a differential revision.
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section covers style guidelines for writing shaders in Godot, focusing on statement formatting.
One statement per line. Never combine multiple statements on a single line.

GDScript:
void fragment() {
    ALBEDO = vec3(1.0);
    EMISSION = vec3(1.0);
}

GDScript:
void fragment() {
    ALBEDO = vec3(1.0); EMISSION = vec3(1.0);
}

The only exception to that rule is the ternary operator:

GDScript:
   void fragment() {
        bool should_be_white = true;
        ALBEDO = should_be_white ? vec3(1.0) : vec3(0.0);
    }
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section covers comment spacing and multiline comment usage in GLSL shaders.
Comment spacing: Regular comments should start with a space, but not code that you comment out. This helps differentiate text comments from disabled code.

Good:
GDScript:
    // This is a comment.
    //return;

Bad:
GDScript:
    //This is a comment.
    // return;

Don't use multiline comment syntax if your comment can fit on a single line:
GDScript:
    /* This is another comment. */
Note: In the shader editor, to make the selected code a comment (or uncomment it), press Ctrl + K. This feature adds or removes // at the start of the selected lines.
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: Explains how to write documentation comments for shader uniforms in Godot.
GDScript:
    /**
     * This is a documentation comment.
     * These lines will appear in the inspector when hovering the shader parameter
     * named "Something".
     * You can use [b]BBCode[/b] [i]formatting[/i] in the comment.
     */
    uniform int something = 1;

These comments will appear when hovering a property in the inspector. If you don't wish the comment to be visible in the inspector, use the standard comment syntax instead (// ... or /* ... */ with only one leading asterisk).
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section of the Shaders Style Guide covers whitespace conventions in GLSL code.

Whitespace
Always use one space around operators and after commas. Also, avoid extraneous spaces in function calls.

GDScript:
    COLOR.r = 5.0;
    COLOR.r = COLOR.g + 0.1;
    COLOR.b = some_function(1.0, 2.0);

Do not use spaces to align expressions vertically.

GDScript:
    ALBEDO.r = 1.0;
    EMISSION.r = 1.0;
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section details the style guide for writing floating-point numbers in Godot shaders.
Floating-point numbers
Always specify at least one digit for both the integer and fractional part. This makes it easier to distinguish floating-point numbers from integers, as well as distinguishing numbers greater than 1 from those lower than 1.

Good:
GDScript:
    void fragment() {
        ALBEDO.rgb = vec3(5.0, 0.1, 0.2);
    }

Bad:
GDScript:
    void fragment() {
        ALBEDO.rgb = vec3(5., .1, .2);
    }
---CHUNK---
Document: Shaders Style Guide
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shaders_style_guide.rst
Summary: This section explains how to access vector members in shaders based on their content.
Use r, g, b, and a when accessing a vector's members if it contains a color. If the vector contains anything else than a color, use x, y, z, and w. This allows those reading your code to better understand what the underlying data represents.

Good:
GDScript:
    COLOR.rgb = vec3(5.0, 0.1, 0.2);

Bad:
GDScript:
    COLOR.xyz = vec3(5.0, 0.1, 0.2);
---CHUNK---
